00:48:26.460 --> 00:48:31.350
What's the story of
this language there now?

00:48:31.350 --> 00:48:35.430
Does anybody have
any [inaudible]

00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:36.980
in the Syriac language?

00:48:36.980 --> 00:48:38.530
&gt;&gt; Joseph J. Palackal: I'm
glad you asked that question,

00:48:38.530 --> 00:48:40.630
but the answer is a sad one.

00:48:40.630 --> 00:48:43.020
The history of the
language is sad.

00:48:43.020 --> 00:48:46.910
Because in the seventh century,
because of the Arabic invasion,

00:48:46.910 --> 00:48:48.950
it was not like Karela.

00:48:48.950 --> 00:48:50.950
There Arabic was imposed.

00:48:50.950 --> 00:48:52.560
So the Syriac that you hear

00:48:52.560 --> 00:48:56.400
from the Middle East now
sounds very different.

00:48:56.400 --> 00:49:02.570
Even the [chanting], it must
have a different flavor there.

00:49:02.570 --> 00:49:05.250
And the memory of the
language is dying out there.

00:49:05.250 --> 00:49:09.420
Whereas in India, there was no
persecution either for the Jews

00:49:09.420 --> 00:49:11.770
or for Christians,
so it survived.

00:49:11.770 --> 00:49:16.530
So probably the history of the
language is redefined in India.

00:49:16.530 --> 00:49:19.830
Some of the melodies may
be more intact in India

00:49:19.830 --> 00:49:21.810
than in the Middle East.

00:49:21.810 --> 00:49:26.930
Now not all the melodies came
from Syria or Middle East.

00:49:26.930 --> 00:49:28.230
There are some melodies there,

00:49:28.230 --> 00:49:30.560
especially the Portuguese
melodies were composed

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:31.860
in Karela.

00:49:31.860 --> 00:49:34.970
There are very few
samples of that.

00:49:34.970 --> 00:49:38.090
So Karela has its
own contribution

00:49:38.090 --> 00:49:41.530
to the music history of India.

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:42.830
Yeah.

00:49:42.830 --> 00:49:44.130
&gt;&gt; One question.

00:49:44.130 --> 00:49:45.430
&gt;&gt; Joseph J. Palackal: Yes.

