00:49:48.030 --> 00:49:52.540
Aramaic, Christian
Aramaic, is known as Syriac.

00:49:52.540 --> 00:49:55.220
The Aramaic language was
a commercial language

00:49:55.220 --> 00:49:56.520
for a long time.

00:49:56.520 --> 00:49:59.490
Remember when Emperor
Ahsoka published the edicts,

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:01.870
Aramaic was one of
the languages.

00:50:01.870 --> 00:50:03.170
Which means there are people

00:50:03.170 --> 00:50:05.370
who knew only Aramaic
in the kingdom.

00:50:05.370 --> 00:50:07.800
Because if you didn't know
the rules of the kingdom,

00:50:07.800 --> 00:50:09.240
your head could be chopped off.

00:50:09.240 --> 00:50:14.320
So just the way we do Chinese
in Chinatown in New York,

00:50:14.320 --> 00:50:17.410
there were Aramaic inscriptions.

00:50:17.410 --> 00:50:21.570
So that was a story there.

00:50:21.570 --> 00:50:25.910
And then -- so it was already
in the history of the language.

00:50:25.910 --> 00:50:30.290
And when Christianity came,
literature in Aramaic came

00:50:30.290 --> 00:50:31.590
to be known as Syriac.

00:50:31.590 --> 00:50:33.170
Political situations changed.

00:50:33.170 --> 00:50:36.700
One major reason
is the translation

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:39.690
of the Septuagint in Greek.

00:50:39.690 --> 00:50:42.690
So Syria Aram, Aramaic,
became Syriac.

00:50:42.690 --> 00:50:45.720
And then it stayed on.

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:48.110
Now there's a move among
St. Thomas Christians

00:50:48.110 --> 00:50:51.380
in many Syriac churches in
Karela to take out the Syrian

00:50:51.380 --> 00:50:54.080
and make it Syriac, because
they don't want association

00:50:54.080 --> 00:50:56.050
with Syria.

00:50:56.050 --> 00:50:59.830
Rather, Syriac Christians.

00:50:59.830 --> 00:51:01.680
Thank you for clarifying
that, yes.

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:02.980
Yes?

00:51:02.980 --> 00:51:04.280
&gt;&gt; How about the Portuguese?

00:51:04.280 --> 00:51:10.700
When they came to
India, did they try

00:51:10.700 --> 00:51:12.000
to suppress and destroy history?

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:13.300
[Inaudible]

00:51:13.300 --> 00:51:14.600
&gt;&gt; Joseph J. Palackal:
There is an element,

00:51:14.600 --> 00:51:15.900
because they challenged us.

00:51:15.900 --> 00:51:17.570
Basically they thought,
"This is not real."

00:51:17.570 --> 00:51:21.310
So they wanted us to change
the language in the Latin

00:51:21.310 --> 00:51:23.260
and chant and all that.

00:51:23.260 --> 00:51:24.580
But we resisted.

00:51:24.580 --> 00:51:30.820
So in the process, one group
broke away from that tradition

00:51:30.820 --> 00:51:33.340
and said, "No, we don't have to
do anything with this people."

00:51:33.340 --> 00:51:38.650
So those are the Akarbites,
the orthodox and all that.

00:51:38.650 --> 00:51:40.490
But we, the Siro
Malabar Christians,

00:51:40.490 --> 00:51:45.270
stayed with the Portuguese
but translated into Syriac

00:51:45.270 --> 00:51:46.570
and kept the incantations.

00:51:46.570 --> 00:51:50.050
So we adopted benediction
of the blessed sacrament,

00:51:50.050 --> 00:51:53.940
we adopted [inaudible] and
we have songs for the --

00:51:53.940 --> 00:51:59.510
the song that the children
sang in [inaudible] is --

00:51:59.510 --> 00:52:11.060
[ Chanting ]

00:52:11.060 --> 00:52:12.430
It's a hymn to the
blessed virgin.

00:52:12.430 --> 00:52:13.930
Probably that was composed

00:52:13.930 --> 00:52:15.760
when we started [inaudible]
and all that.

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:18.720
So we cannot say they
destroyed everything.

00:52:18.720 --> 00:52:21.930
I wouldn't use that
word destroy.

00:52:21.930 --> 00:52:23.670
They challenged us.

00:52:23.670 --> 00:52:25.620
The Siro Malabar Christians
accepted the challenge

00:52:25.620 --> 00:52:29.870
and translated it into
Syriac and moved on.

00:52:29.870 --> 00:52:32.330
So in the history of
music, that became a bone

00:52:32.330 --> 00:52:35.790
because we have a new
branch of music in India.

00:52:35.790 --> 00:52:40.360
And after the Portuguese
left, we didn't do much

00:52:40.360 --> 00:52:43.070
to revive the tradition,
and then we left it.

00:52:43.070 --> 00:52:46.420
We cannot blame anybody
for what we are doing now.

00:52:46.420 --> 00:52:49.650
I'm glad some of our
priests are stepping forward

00:52:49.650 --> 00:52:53.530
to reclaim the Siro
Malabar Church.

00:52:53.530 --> 00:52:56.300
Otherwise the next
generation will have zero.

00:52:56.300 --> 00:52:59.140
So that Siro B stands
for Syriac language.

00:52:59.140 --> 00:53:02.340
So I am glad for priests
like Father Justin

00:53:02.340 --> 00:53:04.800
and his assistant Felix Simon.

00:53:04.800 --> 00:53:07.340
They are trying to
bring it back.

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:09.350
And someday we will
study the history

00:53:09.350 --> 00:53:12.130
of the language in America.

00:53:12.130 --> 00:53:14.520
Amazing. Yes?

00:53:14.520 --> 00:53:21.330
&gt;&gt; Question between the
history of the Catholic

00:53:21.330 --> 00:53:23.330
versus the orthodox Jews.

00:53:23.330 --> 00:53:24.630
Are there differences?

00:53:24.630 --> 00:53:26.500
&gt;&gt; Joseph J. Palackal: Oh yes.

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:27.830
Yes, yes, yes.

00:53:27.830 --> 00:53:30.880
The orthodox Christians
used west Syriac.

00:53:30.880 --> 00:53:33.600
The Catholics, the
Siro Malabar, we use --

00:53:33.600 --> 00:53:36.550
I cannot say Catholic because
Siro Malingula also use

00:53:36.550 --> 00:53:37.850
west Syriac.

00:53:37.850 --> 00:53:40.870
So the Siro Malabar Church,
these two churches --

00:53:40.870 --> 00:53:43.520
there are eight churches
among Sindon Christians.

00:53:43.520 --> 00:53:45.500
Two churches use
Chaldean Syriac.

00:53:45.500 --> 00:53:49.320
So what I am singing, what you
heard here, the whole story

00:53:49.320 --> 00:53:52.170
of Chaldean Syriac, east Syriac.

00:53:52.170 --> 00:53:55.080
West Syriac, the
pronunciation is different.

00:53:55.080 --> 00:53:56.380
The basic difference is

00:53:56.380 --> 00:53:59.010
like British English
and American English.

00:53:59.010 --> 00:54:00.310
[ Inaudible ]

00:54:00.310 --> 00:54:05.120
Yes. Completely different
melodic repertoire.

00:54:05.120 --> 00:54:07.390
They have a very
complex system of music.

00:54:07.390 --> 00:54:10.360
It is much more complex
than this.

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:13.020
They have us practice
this singing,

00:54:13.020 --> 00:54:19.000
one chant in eight different
melodies, octo arcos.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:21.980
[Inaudible] Gregorian chant.

00:54:21.980 --> 00:54:24.690
Same text for different seasons.

00:54:24.690 --> 00:54:27.350
They sing in eight
different tunes.

00:54:27.350 --> 00:54:29.310
Whereas in the eastern
Syriac tradition,

00:54:29.310 --> 00:54:32.940
we sing same melody
with different text.

00:54:32.940 --> 00:54:36.780
What a beautiful
complementarity.

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:38.560
That means we --

00:54:38.560 --> 00:54:41.040
[ Chanting ]

00:54:41.040 --> 00:54:44.830
We apply that to different
texts in the same major

00:54:44.830 --> 00:54:46.170
for different liturgical
context.

00:54:46.170 --> 00:54:48.500
So these are complementary
traditions.

00:54:48.500 --> 00:54:50.100
It enriches the world.

00:54:50.100 --> 00:54:54.200
But for example, to be specific,

00:54:54.200 --> 00:55:01.030
eastern Syriac will say
[foreign phrase], Holy God.

00:55:01.030 --> 00:55:02.330
[Foreign word] is God.

00:55:02.330 --> 00:55:07.510
West Syriac will say
[foreign phrase].

00:55:07.510 --> 00:55:11.040
[ Foreign language ]

00:55:11.040 --> 00:55:14.050
Glory be to the father and
the son and the Holy Spirit.

00:55:14.050 --> 00:55:16.090
[ Foreign language ]

00:55:16.090 --> 00:55:19.510
Whereas we will say --

00:55:19.510 --> 00:55:24.040
[ Foreign language ]

00:55:24.040 --> 00:55:26.390
Such differences, yes.

00:55:26.390 --> 00:55:29.040
This world of music,

00:55:29.040 --> 00:55:31.640
Syriac music is more
complex than we think.

00:55:31.640 --> 00:55:33.940
Thank you for that question.

00:55:42.050 --> 00:55:44.890
Yes, please.

00:55:44.890 --> 00:55:49.150
&gt;&gt; This really isn't
a musical question,

00:55:49.150 --> 00:55:51.810
so I'm not sure I should ask it.

00:55:51.810 --> 00:56:00.470
But I was struck by the fact
that in the church there seemed

00:56:00.470 --> 00:56:04.020
to be many statues, but I didn't
see anything resembling the

00:56:04.020 --> 00:56:07.390
icons that one sees in
the eastern orthodox

00:56:07.390 --> 00:56:09.380
and of course many
oriental orthodoxies.

00:56:09.380 --> 00:56:10.680
&gt;&gt; Joseph J. Palackal:
Good observation.

00:56:10.680 --> 00:56:11.980
Because these are from
the Siro Malabar churches,

00:56:11.980 --> 00:56:13.280
which was Latinized.

00:56:13.280 --> 00:56:14.580
So most of the segments
are from that tradition.

00:56:14.580 --> 00:56:15.880
That's why you see that.

00:56:15.880 --> 00:56:17.180
Good observation.

00:56:17.180 --> 00:56:18.480
Thank you.

